Steaming Cup of Coffee

 
 
 

Java CC Monthly Newsletter - June 2019

We are excited to inform you that the next issue of our Monthly Newsletter is now live!
In case you have missed some of our weekly newsletters, here is a recap of the most important news and articles in June selected by Java CC.

 
 
 
 

Java Trends Report - July 2019

This article provides a summary of how the InfoQ editorial team currently see adoption of technology and emerging trends within the Java space, which focuses not just on Java the language but also on related languages like Kotlin and Scala, the Java Virtual Machine (JVM), and Java-based frameworks and utilities.
You can read more on trends in core Java, such as the adoption of Java 11 and 12, and also the evolution of web-based frameworks like Spring Boot and MicroProfile.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Towards Better Serialization

Java's serialization facility is a bit of a paradox. On the one hand, it was probably critical to Java's success, on the other hand,  it makes nearly every mistake imaginable, and poses an ongoing tax for library maintainers, language developers, and users.
In this document by Brian Goetz  you will explore a possible direction for improving serialization in the Java Platform.

 
 
 
 
 
 

Time to Upgrade 

 
 
 
 
 

IntelliJ IDEA 2019.2 is Released

A major upgrade of IntelliJ IDEA  - version 2019.2 – is out! With this release,
IntelliJ IDEA gets a load of awesome new features and improvements.
It includes startup performance optimisations, improved profiling tools, shell scripts support, improved code completion and refactoring, improved VCS integration and much more.
You can also check how to get started with Java 13 enhanced switch expressions and text blocks.

 
 

There Is Always More to Learn

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 

The Ultimate Guide to Java Stream API Collectors

All you need to know about Java Stream API Collectors. This guide aims to be your friendly neighbourhood complete Collectors reference, additionally covering changes introduced in separate Java releases.

 
 
 
 
 

Never NOT Learning 

Why does a JavaChampion not know this? No matter how long you have been working with Java you can always be surprised by some of its features. Like the ones described in this article. 

 
 
 
 
 

Fallbacks Are Overrated - Architecting For Resilience

Fallbacks in circuit breakers replace failure with some pre-configured response so that the scope of the malfunction is limited and hidden from the end user. However, in real life, a naïve fallback is often too simple and either confusing or unacceptable.
In this article you can see more robust approach to handling failures, compensating for broken transactions in the future.

 
 
 
 
 
 

Service Mesh: Past, Present, and Future

Microservices architectural trend introduced challenges inherent within distributed systems that transfer data over an unreliable and heterogeneous network, such as the difficulty of implementing cross-cutting communication concerns that were previously included within the monolithic codebase, like security, reliability, and observability.
This amazing minibook will introduce service meshes and help you choose if, when, and how to deploy a service mesh. 

 
 
 
 
 

Mapping
BLOBs and CLOBs with
Hibernate and JPA

Databases use the data types BLOB (binary large object) and CLOB (character large object) to store large objects, like images and very long texts. JPA and Hibernate provide two kinds of mappings for these types. Check them in action here!

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Spring Boot: Where Do the Default Metrics Come From?

Have you ever noticed all of the default metrics Spring Boot and Micrometer generate for your app? If not — you can add the actuator dependency to your project and hit the /actuator/metrics endpoint where you will find useful info about the JVM, processes, Tomcat, traffic, and so on. 
If you have ever wondered how these metrics end up there, and where we can find an explanation about what params they describe, then this is a post for you.

 
 
 
 
 

Maximizing Performance with GraalVM

When projects become bigger, you might want to split you codebase into multiple build modules for better maintainability and understandability. This article shows you how to split up a Spring Boot application into multiple build modules with Gradle. You are going to examine what modules are and why you need them in the first place with the help of an example application.

 
 
 
 
 
 

Kotlin Flows Series

Reactive Streams is an impressive piece of engineering. It brings asynchronous event streams with back-pressure to the JVM world, which otherwise lacks platform support for asynchrony.
Its alternative in Kotlin - Kotlin Flows is intended to have a simpler design and allow everyone to write asynchronous operators. 
In these series you will read more on:
    •  Comparison between Reactive Streams and Kotlin Flows
    •  Execution Context of Kotlin Flows
    •  Callbacks and Kotlin Flows
    •  ​Exceptions in Kotlin Flows

 
 
 
 
 
 

Testing Spring Boot Conditionals:
The Sane Way

Testing Spring Boot conditionals can drive you crazy as testing such conditions (and their combinations) can get messy. In this article you will discover some possible (arguably, sane) ways to approach that.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Maven Scopes and Gradle Configurations Explained

One of the key features of a build tool for Java is dependency management. Once you declare a third party dependency it is then important how it is added to the classpath at the right times in the build lifecycle. Explore the flexibility of both Maven and Gradle regarding declaring dependencies here.

A Look at Java Optionals

The purpose of the Optional class is to provide a type-level solution for representing optional values instead of null references.
In this blog post you will learn more about Java Optionals and how to effectively utilise its API.
